spolia from the war against Cleopatra, then as costly wares exchanged over the expanding Roman trade routes. In this respect, Romans treated Egyptian art surprisingly similarly to Greek art. By examining the concrete mechanisms through which Egyptian objects were acquired and displayed in Rome, this book offers a new understanding of this impressive material at the crossroads of Hellenistic, Roman, and Egyptian culture.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aArt objects, EgyptianzRome. 0aArtxCollectors and collectingzItalyzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aArtxCollectors and collectingzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aArt, EgyptianzItalyzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aArt, EgyptianzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHandel. 4aPompeji. 4aRom / Antike. 4aWandmalerei. 4aÄgypten / Altertum. 4aÄgypten / Artefakt. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aEgyptian objects.  aPompeii.  aRoman trade.  awall painting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishz978311075405608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021z9783110753813oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831107009300 cprintz978311070040440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311070089340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110700893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110700893/original  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1